<h1><mark>Mini Biography:Science</mark></h1>
<p>Science is both a systematic process of discovery and a body of knowledge about the natural world, driven by observation, experimentation, and evidence-based reasoning.</p>

<h2><mark>How science started?</h2></mark></h2>
<p>Observation of Nature and Curiosity: Ancient humans started science by carefully observing natural phenomena such as the movement of the sun and stars, seasonal patterns, plant growth, and animal behavior. These observations led to early explanations of the world and practical applications like agriculture, tool-making, and medicine. Civilizations like the Egyptians, Babylonians, and Chinese developed knowledge systems based on patterns and empirical evidence, forming the first steps toward scientific inquiry.
Formalization and Experimentation: Science advanced when thinkers began to organize knowledge methodically and test ideas through reasoning and experiments. Ancient Greek philosophers such as Thales, Aristotle, and later Ptolemy and Archimedes emphasized logical reasoning, measurement, and systematic investigation. This approach evolved through the Islamic Golden Age and Renaissance Europe, eventually leading to the scientific method, where hypotheses are tested and knowledge is built on evidence.</p>
<p><small><b>Note:</b>Science started from basic human curiosity about nature, was shaped by ancient reasoning and empirical practices, and became a formalized, systematic method during the Scientific Revolution, laying the foundation for the modern scientific pursuits that continue to expand human understanding.</small></p>

<h2><mark>Important achievements</mark></h2>
<p>The Scientific Method – A systematic approach to observation, experimentation, and evidence-based conclusions that underpins modern science</p>
<p>Understanding Gravity – Isaac Newton formulated the law of gravity, later expanded by Albert Einstein through the theory of relativity.</p>
<p>Theory of Evolution – Charles Darwin explained how species evolve through natural selection.</p>
<p>Discovery of DNA – Identifying the double-helix structure of DNA revolutionized genetics, medicine, and biotechnology.</p>


